142struct BranchTarget {
143 BranchTarget()
144 : block(nullptr)
145 , count(PNaN)
146 {
147 }
148
149 explicit BranchTarget(BasicBlock* block)
150 : block(block)
151 , count(PNaN)
152 {
153 }
154
155 void setBytecodeIndex(unsigned bytecodeIndex)
156 {
157 block = bitwise_cast<BasicBlock*>(static_cast<uintptr_t>(bytecodeIndex));
158 }
159 unsigned bytecodeIndex() const { return bitwise_cast<uintptr_t>(block); }
160
161 void dump(PrintStream&) const;
162
163 BasicBlock* block;
164 float count;
165};
166
167struct BranchData {
168 static BranchData withBytecodeIndices(
169 unsigned takenBytecodeIndex, unsigned notTakenBytecodeIndex)
170 {
171 BranchData result;
172 result.taken.block = bitwise_cast<BasicBlock*>(static_cast<uintptr_t>(takenBytecodeIndex));
173 result.notTaken.block = bitwise_cast<BasicBlock*>(static_cast<uintptr_t>(notTakenBytecodeIndex));
174 return result;
175 }
176
177 unsigned takenBytecodeIndex() const { return taken.bytecodeIndex(); }
178 unsigned notTakenBytecodeIndex() const { return notTaken.bytecodeIndex(); }
179
180 BasicBlock*& forCondition(bool condition)
181 {
182 if (condition)
183 return taken.block;
184 return notTaken.block;
185 }
186
187 BranchTarget taken;
188 BranchTarget notTaken;
189};

191// The SwitchData and associated data structures duplicate the information in
192// JumpTable. The DFG may ultimately end up using the JumpTable, though it may
193// instead decide to do something different - this is entirely up to the DFG.
194// These data structures give the DFG a higher-level semantic description of
195// what is going on, which will allow it to make the right decision.
196//
197// Note that there will never be multiple SwitchCases in SwitchData::cases that
198// have the same SwitchCase::value, since the bytecode's JumpTables never have
199// duplicates - since the JumpTable maps a value to a target. It's a
200// one-to-many mapping. So we may have duplicate targets, but never duplicate
201// values.
202struct SwitchCase {
203 SwitchCase()
204 {
205 }
206
207 SwitchCase(LazyJSValue value, BasicBlock* target)
208 : value(value)
209 , target(target)
210 {
211 }
212
213 static SwitchCase withBytecodeIndex(LazyJSValue value, unsigned bytecodeIndex)
214 {
215 SwitchCase result;
216 result.value = value;
217 result.target.setBytecodeIndex(bytecodeIndex);
218 return result;
219 }
220
221 LazyJSValue value;
222 BranchTarget target;
223};
224
225struct SwitchData {
226 // Initializes most fields to obviously invalid values. Anyone
227 // constructing this should make sure to initialize everything they
228 // care about manually.
229 SwitchData()
230 : switchTableIndex(UINT_MAX)
231 , kind(static_cast<SwitchKind>(-1))
232 , didUseJumpTable(false)
233 {
234 }
235
236 Vector<SwitchCase> cases;
237 BranchTarget fallThrough;
238 size_t switchTableIndex;
239 SwitchKind kind;
240 bool didUseJumpTable;
241};

251struct LoadVarargsData {
252 VirtualRegister start; // Local for the first element. This is the first actual argument, not this.
253 VirtualRegister count; // Local for the count.
254 VirtualRegister machineStart;

256 unsigned offset; // Which array element to start with. Usually this is 0.
257 unsigned mandatoryMinimum; // The number of elements on the stack that must be initialized; if the array is too short then the missing elements must get undefined. Does not include "this".
258 unsigned limit; // Maximum number of elements to load. Includes "this".
259};

415 void setOp(NodeType op)
416 {
417 m_op = op;

420 void setFlags(NodeFlags flags)
421 {
422 m_flags = flags;
423 }
424
425 bool mergeFlags(NodeFlags flags)
426 {
427 NodeFlags newFlags = m_flags | flags;
428 if (newFlags == m_flags)
429 return false;
430 m_flags = newFlags;
431 return true;
432 }
433
434 bool filterFlags(NodeFlags flags)
435 {
436 NodeFlags newFlags = m_flags & flags;
437 if (newFlags == m_flags)
438 return false;
439 m_flags = newFlags;
440 return true;
441 }
442
443 bool clearFlags(NodeFlags flags)
444 {
445 return filterFlags(~flags);
446 }
447
448 void setResult(NodeFlags result)
449 {
450 ASSERT(!(result & ~NodeResultMask));
451 clearFlags(NodeResultMask);
452 mergeFlags(result);
453 }
454
455 NodeFlags result() const
456 {
457 return flags() & NodeResultMask;
458 }

509 bool mustGenerate() const

518
519 bool isConstant()
520 {
521 switch (op()) {
522 case JSConstant:
523 case DoubleConstant:
524 case Int52Constant:
525 return true;
526 default:
527 return false;
528 }
529 }
530
531 bool hasConstant()
532 {
533 switch (op()) {
534 case CheckIsConstant:
535 case JSConstant:
536 case DoubleConstant:
537 case Int52Constant:
538 return true;
539
540 case PhantomDirectArguments:
541 case PhantomClonedArguments:
542 // These pretend to be the empty value constant for the benefit of the DFG backend, which
543 // otherwise wouldn't take kindly to a node that doesn't compute a value.
544 return true;
545
546 default:
547 return false;
548 }
549 }
550
551 FrozenValue* constant()
552 {
553 ASSERT(hasConstant());
554
555 if (op() == PhantomDirectArguments || op() == PhantomClonedArguments) {
556 // These pretend to be the empty value constant for the benefit of the DFG backend, which
557 // otherwise wouldn't take kindly to a node that doesn't compute a value.
558 return FrozenValue::emptySingleton();
559 }
560
561 return m_opInfo.as<FrozenValue*>();
562 }

564 // Don't call this directly - use Graph::convertToConstant() instead!
565 void convertToConstant(FrozenValue* value)
566 {
567 if (hasDoubleResult())
568 m_op = DoubleConstant;
569 else if (hasInt52Result())
570 m_op = Int52Constant;
571 else
572 m_op = JSConstant;
573 m_flags &= ~(NodeMustGenerate | NodeHasVarArgs);
574 m_opInfo = value;
575 children.reset();
576 }

1190 // This corrects the arithmetic node flags, so that irrelevant bits are
1191 // ignored. In particular, anything other than ArithMul or ValueMul does not need
1192 // to know if it can speculate on negative zero.
1193 NodeFlags arithNodeFlags()
1194 {
1195 NodeFlags result = m_flags & NodeArithFlagsMask;
1196 if (op() == ArithMul || op() == ArithDiv || op() == ValueDiv || op() == ArithMod || op() == ArithNegate || op() == ArithPow || op() == ArithRound || op() == ArithFloor || op() == ArithCeil || op() == ArithTrunc || op() == DoubleAsInt32 || op() == ValueNegate || op() == ValueMul || op() == ValueDiv)
1197 return result;
1198 return result & ~NodeBytecodeNeedsNegZero;
1199 }

1641 unsigned numSuccessors()
1642 {
1643 switch (op()) {
1644 case Jump:
1645 return 1;
1646 case Branch:
1647 return 2;
1648 case Switch:
1649 return switchData()->cases.size() + 1;
1650 case EntrySwitch:
1651 return entrySwitchData()->cases.size();
1652 default:
1653 return 0;
1654 }
1655 }
1656
1657 BasicBlock*& successor(unsigned index)
1658 {
1659 if (isSwitch()) {
1660 if (index < switchData()->cases.size())
1661 return switchData()->cases[index].target.block;
1662 RELEASE_ASSERT(index == switchData()->cases.size());
1663 return switchData()->fallThrough.block;
1664 } else if (isEntrySwitch())
1665 return entrySwitchData()->cases[index];
1666
1667 switch (index) {
1668 case 0:
1669 if (isJump())
1670 return targetBlock();
1671 return branchData()->taken.block;
1672 case 1:
1673 return branchData()->notTaken.block;
1674 default:
1675 RELEASE_ASSERT_NOT_REACHED();
1676 return targetBlock();
1677 }
1678 }

2552 bool shouldSpeculateInt52()
2553 {
2554 // We have to include SpecInt32Only here for two reasons:
2555 // 1. We diligently write code that first checks if we should speculate Int32.
2556 // For example:
2557 // if (shouldSpeculateInt32()) ...
2558 // else if (shouldSpeculateInt52()) ...
2559 // This means we it's totally valid to speculate Int52 when we're dealing
2560 // with a type that's the union of Int32 and Int52.
2561 //
2562 // It would be a performance mistake to not include Int32 here because we obviously
2563 // have variables that are the union of Int32 and Int52 values, and it's better
2564 // to speculate Int52 than double in that situation.
2565 //
2566 // 2. We also write code where we ask if the inputs can be Int52, like if
2567 // we know via profiling that an Add overflows, we may not emit an Int32 add.
2568 // However, we only emit such an add if both inputs can be Int52, and Int32
2569 // can trivially become Int52.
2570 //
2571 return enableInt52() && isInt32OrInt52Speculation(prediction());
2572 }

3364template<typename T>
3365CString nodeMapDump(const T& nodeMap, DumpContext* context = nullptr)
3366{
3367 Vector<typename T::KeyType> keys;
3368 for (
3369 typename T::const_iterator iter = nodeMap.begin();
3370 iter != nodeMap.end(); ++iter)
3371 keys.append(iter->key);
3372 std::sort(keys.begin(), keys.end(), NodeComparator());
3373 StringPrintStream out;
3374 CommaPrinter comma;
3375 for(unsigned i = 0; i < keys.size(); ++i)
3376 out.print(comma, keys[i], "=>", inContext(nodeMap.get(keys[i]), context));
3377 return out.toCString();
3378}
3379
3380template<typename T>
3381CString nodeValuePairListDump(const T& nodeValuePairList, DumpContext* context = nullptr)
3382{
3383 using V = typename T::ValueType;
3384 T sortedList = nodeValuePairList;
3385 std::sort(sortedList.begin(), sortedList.end(), [](const V& a, const V& b) {
3386 return NodeComparator()(a.node, b.node);
3387 });
3388
3389 StringPrintStream out;
3390 CommaPrinter comma;
3391 for (const auto& pair : sortedList)
3392 out.print(comma, pair.node, "=>", inContext(pair.value, context));
3393 return out.toCString();
3394}
